entry.title: [AsyncSB] Use AsyncCheckTracker to determine if main page load is blocked.
entry.content:
When SafeBrowsingAsyncRealTimeCheck is enabled, whether the main page

load is blocked cannot be determined solely by is_subresource and

threat_type, because the page load is no longer blocked by the check

deterministically. Going forward, AsyncCheckTracker will be

responsible for monitoring the status of the navigation and inform

whether the main page load is blocked. The old function is renamed

to IsMainPageLoadPendingWithSyncCheck so it is clear that it only

works when async check is disabled.



To replace all current usage of UnsafeResource::IsMainPageLoadBlocked

with AsyncCheckTracker::IsMainPageLoadPending, this CL makes the

following changes to avoid dependency issue:

* unsafe_resource_util is bubbled up from security_interstitials/ to

safe_browsing/ so it can depend on AsyncCheckTracker.

* The client_report_util target is merged into its parent browser

target to avoid circular dependency.



Also avoid using the word "blocked" going forward, since it can also

mean this URL is dangerous so it is "blocked" by Safe Browsing,

whereas here it means the navigation is "blocked" because the check

has not yet completed. Therefore, IsMainPageLoadBlocked is renamed to

IsMainPageLoadPending.



There is no behavioral change in this CL. The actual implementation of

AsyncCheckTracker::IsMainPageLoadPending will be done in a follow up CL.

entry.content:
This CL makes ClientControlledState (CCState) update the snap ratio

based on the requested bounds.

`window_->GetTargetBounds()`. But because CCState doesn’t immediately

update the bounds (and state type of course) on WMEvent, the ratio is

calculated based on the obsolete bounds.

Therefore, we want CCState to update the ratio based on the requested

snapped bounds.

entry.title: RTCVDAdapter: Fallback due to small resolution in media thread
entry.content:
WebRTC video decoder fallbacks a hardware decoder to a software

decoder when the number of the hardware decoders is more than 8 and

the resolution is less than 320x240 on non ChromeOS. The resolution

of a frame is detected when the frame is decoded. Therefore the

fallback due to the low resolution is reported in the second frame.

The second frame is not keyframe and thus it is necessary to request

a keyframe to an sender side. This increases the start up time in a

webrtc video call.

To resolve the issue, we would rather check the resolution in webrtc

decoder thread before decoding by parsing the stream.

Libgav1 is newly built on Android to parse av1 stream. This increases

the chrome binary size by 41283 bytes.

entry.title: Workaround Max Texture Size on Android

If the runtime gives us a recommendedImageRectWidth that is greater than

rendering artifacts, because a single eye will cover more than half of

entry.title: bind_internal.h cleanup: Guard remaining static_asserts.
entry.content:
Most existing static_asserts have already been guarded using the

"assert inside lambda inside templated struct inside std::conjunction"

trick already documented in bind.h. However, three asserts that

indicated Bind misuse (as opposed to invariants inside the Bind

machinery) had not been so guarded, and I tripped over some of them

while trying to refactor. So guard them too.



The net effect is that Yet More Cases of misuse will only print one

failing static_assert and no further compiler errors. This also ensures

the result of BindOnce()/BindRepeating() is always a

BindFailedCheckPreviousErrors in such cases, instead of often being

void. That in turn makes downstream usage/handling more consistent.

entry.title: [Exo] Address crash when Flush() is called during disconnect
entry.content:
Currently there are circumstances under which ash/exo will crash if

the server attempts to Flush() the client buffer at the wrong time.



Flush() should be an idempotent operation and the server should not

need to perform any state checks before requesting a buffer flush.

However currently exo will crash if the client disconnects and

there are still events persisted in the client buffer.



See the linked bug for more detail into how this results in crashes

and what the expected behavior is.



This CL guards against this failure case by checking to make sure

the client has not initiated its destruction procedure before

flushing the buffer.



The correct fix requires changes to the upstream libwayland library

to make it aware of client destruction and handle these cases

appropriately. This will be addressed in a follow-up.

entry.title: [exo] Fix DestroyRootSurfaceBeforeCommit unittest
entry.content:
Currently this test destroys the surface before destroying the

remote surface role. This order of operations is incorrect as it

violates the destruction order of the surface and its role (remote

surface) as indicated in the spec [1].



Further, asking to pin the remote surface after the surface has been

destroyed is incorrect and results in immediate client disconnect /

destruction during the test (which is not intended).



This fixes the test by moving destruction after the pinning operation

so that pinning and destruction are tested correctly before a surface

commit.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/wayland/src/protocol/wayland.xml;l=1387;drc=68842b34039eb8efb6b7677cba5a0ddfceac34e0

entry.title: [Files F2] Improve performance for the new tree
entry.content:
1. Do partial children entry scan when possible.

* Add a new action producer which only reads partial children

`readSubDirectoriesToCheckDirectoryChildren`: when the tree

item is not expanded, all we need to know is if the tree item

has child directory or not so we can decide whether or not to

show expand icon. This new action producer will scan the entry

as normal, but returns immediately after finding a directory

child.

* When the tree item renders, it only reads partial children to

know if expand icon should be displayed or not (with the

`mayHaveChildren` property). The full children scan only happens

when it's expanded.

2. Pair both reading action producers with `keyedKeepLatest`

concurrency model to make sure if there's a new scan with the

same entry happening, then the ongoing scan will be cancelled.

3. Do not render children if the item is not expanded (Google Drive

is the only exception because changing that will end up updating

all related browser tests, add a TODO there).



Note: some browser tests are updated because in order to assert

children items we now need to expand the parent first, because we

don't render any children when parent item is not expanded.

entry.title: Remove CSS Zoom Adjustment for GetClientRect
entry.content:
This patch is a follow up for crrev.con/c/5085708, implementing the same

logic that was added to GetBoundingClientRect in GetClientRect.



This change modifies the behavior of the call for elements with a CSS

property. Previously, the dimensions of the quad returned by

GetClientRect were adjusted to the effective zoom of an

element, which is the combination of the page zoom and the CSS zoom.

This meant that the dimensions were not affected by either of those

values.



This had the unintended consequence of causing two elements with the

same size before zoom, but with different zoom properties, to have the

same sized Client Rects, even though they had different sizes on the

page.



The new behavior adjusts the quad to the page's zoom, but not to

the CSS zoom. This means that two elements with the same size before

zoom, but with different zoom properties, will now have different sized

Client Rects.

entry.title: [OG] Fix wrong decision in startup
entry.content:
Currently, when browser starts up but OptimizationGuide has not yet

received the hint component from component updater, OptimizationGuide

has no idea what OptimizationTypes might have a filter associated with

it. At this time, if there is an attempt to check against any filter

of any OptimizationTypes, OptimizationGuide will return

kNoHintAvailable as OptimizationTypeDecision instead of

kHadOptimizationFilterButNotLoadedInTime which is more proper.



This CL fixes this issue by adding a prefs entry to store

OptimizationTypes that had filter in previous sessions, so that the

correct OptimizationTypeDecision will be returned even if the attempt

to check against filter happens before component is available.

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 12).
entry.content:
When the kAppServiceStorage flag is enabled, AppService blocks the

app publishers creating until it's ready, after reading from the

AppStorage file, e.g. ExtensionEventObserverTest.*.



The reason is that TestingProfileManager is created, which builds a

local state pref. During the system shutdown stages,

TestingProfileManager is destroyed before TestingProfile created by

ChromeRenderViewHostTestHarness. So when

ChromeRenderViewHostTestHarness shutdown, it reports error, as the

ExtensionApps publisher of the TestingProfile created by

ChromeRenderViewHostTestHarness still uses the local state pref of

TestingProfileManager.



Modify the test code to move `local_state` of TestingProfileManager

to the test code, and free `local_state` after

ChromeRenderViewHostTestHarness shutdown.
